Landscape_Description: Other (please describe in the comments section)
Type_of_Forest_at_Site: A mixture of evergreen and deciduous trees
Presence_of_Slope: No, the surrounding terrain is relatively flat
Site_Comments: Anastasia Island is a barrier island off the coast of St Augustine, FL. There is a mix of housing and multi-unit apartments and condos along the Atlantic and marsh-wetlands (intracoastal waterway [west] side) with little industry present. There are large tracts of state owned natural terrain including oak forest, pine and red cedar, cypress and naturally occuring sand dune vegetation on the beach which is protected.Spartina sp is the predominant grass in the wetlands marsh. Where the old dune occurs one finds mature oak, magnolia and cedar. Pine and bay predominate in areas that have been disturbed by clearing and fire. There are numerous invasive species, most notably Brazilian Pepper (Schinus sp.). We are in agricultural hardiness Zone 9a and generally enjoy several additional degrees of protection from cold weather due to the proximity of surrounding warm waters. The freezing weather of Feb 2009 was hard on most vegetation as we had several consecutive days of 8 or more hours of hard freeze. I have noted very few butterflies and less abundance of other common insects, most probably due to demise during the freezing weather. [This note written March 20, 2009]
